cletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes was born in 1410, in Suffolk, England. She married Thomas Clare in 1431, in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1465, in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55, and was buried in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1410–will processed 1465":"1410–1465","1408–1463":"1408–1463","1442–1500":"1442–1500","1410–1465":"1410–1465","WP 1465":"1465","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","will processed 1463":"1463","1465":"1465","1431":"1431","1442":"1442","will processed 1465":"1465","1463":"1463","1408":"1408","Little Livermore, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Little Livermore, Essex, England":"Essex, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1410–will processed 1465":"1410–1465","1408–1463":"1408–1463","1